What happens here is when serialising, jackson tries to serialise each reference of one side from the other side. This has caused the recursion.

You can add `@JsonIgnore` annotation to one of the entity to stop this. For your case, looks like better to add `@JsonIgnore` to the `movie` property in `MovieCast` entity. Your code will look like this.

```java
@Entity
@Data
public class MovieCast {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
    private Long castId;

    @OneToOne(mappedBy = &quot;movieCasts&quot;)
    @JsonIgnore
    private Movie movie;
    private String director;
    private String producer;
    private String leadActor;
    private String leadActress;
    private String[] otherActors;
}


@Repository
public class MovieEntityRepo {

    @PersistenceContext
    private EntityManager em;


    public Movie findByName(String name) {
        return em.find(Movie.class, name);
    }
}
```

There are two similar issues with your code. Both result in an infinit loop and stackoverflow.

 1. JSON serialization - this can be solved by adding `@JsonIgnore` as already explained in another answer.
 2. Java `toString()` method. Both entities have this method generated by `Lombok` with `@Data` annotation.

**Solution**

Add `@ToString.Exclude` annotation to the Movie field like this:
```
@OneToOne(mappedBy = &quot;movieCasts&quot;)
@JsonIgnore
@ToString.Exclude
private Movie movie;
```

